@mentat9 Can you override the two failing required CIs (Swagger LintDiff and TypeSpec Validation)?

Regarding Swagger LintDiff - those all appear to be false positives, as it's comparing the new API version to the last API version (a GA version) instead of the last preview API version.

Regarding TypeSpec validation - I implemented the fixes for this API version, but the CI is also including files that are not being touched in this PR.

**[4.1]** Potential bug: when `Properties` is null, the setter silently ignores the assigned value. The generated `ContainerRegistryData` uses the pattern `if (Properties is null) Properties = new ...();` to auto-initialize before setting. This setter should do the same to avoid silently dropping values.

Suggested fix:
```csharp
set
{
    if (Properties is null)
        Properties = new WebhookProperties(Array.Empty<ContainerRegistryWebhookAction>());
    Properties.Scope = value;
}
```

**[4.1]** Same issue here — the `Status` setter also silently drops values when `Properties` is null. Should auto-initialize `Properties` before assigning.

Suggested fix:
```csharp
set
{
    if (Properties is null)
        Properties = new WebhookProperties(Array.Empty<ContainerRegistryWebhookAction>());
    Properties.Status = value;
}
```

I'd hoped that we can add instructions to let agent add convenience code automatically (at least for resources that already have such).

Live test may be a harder problem. (there are more and more restrictions on Playground subscription)

@XiaofeiCao

These list samples buffer the entire pageable result into memory, which can be problematic for subscriptions with large result sets and can make “quickstart” runs appear slow/hung. Prefer streaming output inside the `for await` loop (or collecting only the first N items) to keep memory bounded and make progress visible during execution.
```suggestion
  for await (const item of client.pipelineRuns.list("myResourceGroup", "myRegistry")) {
    console.log(item);
  }
```
